onto Kings Broth agar plates.<\/div><div class = \"text-block\">Top tip: If you are recovering too few bacteria you can increase the volume of supernatant used on the plate. Conversely, if you have too much serially diluted the bacterial (1:10).<\/div><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"#FFED92","section_duration":0,"critical":[{"id":3,"title":"Pipetting","icon":"PipettingIcon"}],"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":988161,"guid":"C07AA5D0CF2E11EA883355FA554DADD6","previous_id":988160,"previous_guid":"4894AD90CF2E11EA883355FA554DADD6","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"2F1FE2C338A24B82BB97030BC0EF4B92","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":"Measuring bacterial load in seeds"}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"7B4E38DA53244AEBA831719FD87131DF","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">To calculate bacterial load:<\/div><div class = \"text-block\">bacterial load = [colony-forming units on plate] x [dilution factor] \/ [seed weight]<\/div><div class = \"text-block\">Example:<\/div><div class = \"text-block\">5 [colony forming units] x 1,000 [dilution factor] \/ 250 mg = 20 colony forming units\/mg of tissue.<\/div><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"#FFED92","section_duration":0,"critical":[{"id":7,"title":"Analyze","icon":"AnalyzeIcon"}],"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":1139866,"guid":"474E07D0802A11EB9D04ED0B76262865","previous_id":968704,"previous_guid":"4F320870B6E011EAA3F7DFAECD6C5497","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"6C06A61FDA8A40D28F002D73EEDC5A00","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":"Sterlising seeds"}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"35D8EA5767AE43CD9598F7254621C216","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">Wash seeds in a 75% ethanol solution for 2 minutes and decant the ethanol.<\/div><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"#94EBFF","section_duration":0,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0}],"document":"","materials":[],"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\"><span>Seed contamination represents a critical route for the transmission of bacterial plant diseases. Here we have created a step-by-step protocol for <\/span><span style = \"font-style:italic;\">in vitro<\/span><span> seed infections of <\/span><span style = \"font-style:italic;\">Pseudomonas syringae. <\/span><span>This protocol provides a robust method for <\/span><span style = \"font-style:italic;\">P. syringae<\/span><span> infection in cucumber. This synthetic seed infection assay is generally applicable for <\/span><span style = \"font-style:italic;\">P. syringae<\/span><span> as we have successfully adapted it for both tomato and soybean.<\/span><\/div><\/div>","changed_on":1615643045}